Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset has 13 variables and 1599 observations.All of the variables are numeric except quality which is an integer.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

1)As most of the variables in the dataset have different chemical properties our main interest will be to understand which chemical properties influence the quality rating of the red wine.

2)Main interest will be on volatile acidity and citric acid as these relate to tase and freshness of the wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Any other chemical variables could impact the quality rating. I think that having so many wines rated a 5 or 6 will make it challenging to put together a strong model.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

1)I have created a new column by dividing them into four categories based on pH value of the wine.(High,Moderately High,Medium,Low)

2)I created Another column quality rating based on quality variable which has three distinct categories: (bad: 3,4), (average: 5,6), (excellent: 7,8)

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did

you do this?

They are few features which are right skewed(Alcohol,Free SO2 and Total SO2, Residual sugar,chlorides and sulphates).I have performed log transformations and looked close to normal distribution.I did this to see if it would become more normally distributed, so that it could potentially be more useful in a model, or in a graph.

Citric acid also had a noticeable right skew, but the log transformation simply made it into left skewed. The square root transformation resulted in a distribution that was closer to normal, except for the spike in zero values. Due to this pattern, I’m not sure this transformed variable will be useful.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

I have made use of ggpairs and ggcorplot to get a better understanding of the relationships between various variables in the given data.

Here volatile acidity and citric acid are negatively correlated.It means fresher wines have less bitter taste of acitic acid.

Some of the top positive and negative correlations with quality include:

Positive Relationship :

1)Alcohol : 0.48

2)Fixed Acidity: 0.12

3)Sulphates : 0.25

4)Citric Acid : 0.23

Negative Relationship :

1)Volatile Acidity : -0.39

2)Total Sulfur dioxide : -0.19

3)Density : -0.17

4)Chlorides : -0.13

Some other interesting facts in the boxplots :

1)The lesser the pH value the better the quality of the wine.As the median value has decreased gradually from bad quality rating to good quality rating.

2)Citric acid which adds freshness to the wine has positive effect in wine as median increased from bad quality to good quality wines.

3)Though pH is less for good quality wines it doesn’t have a signifiacnt change in median value from bad wine to good wine.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

1)Residual sugar has not a significant correlation coefficient with the quality.

2)pH vs fixed acidity,volatile acidity vs citric acid and pH vs citric acid were negatively correlated.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest ralationship was between fixed acidity and pH which has correlation of -0.68.

Reflection

The Red wine dataset has 1599 observations,13 variables which has 11 chemical properties.Here we are mainly interested in features which are correlated with quality.It is given that most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale so it did not have much effect on quality.Alcohol content appeared to be the number one factor for determining an excellent wine.Volatile acidity essentially made a wine bad in large amounts,as large amounts of acetic acid create a bitter taste.WWhile plotting histograms of the chemical properties I have came across few plots which are not normally distributed and right skewed.As for linear and logistic regression we want to make sure that input and output variables is almost liner.For this purpose I have choosen log10 transformation on data as it affects the magnitude of the coefficient that corresponds to the logged variable, but it doesn’t affect the value of the outcome.Next I have created a column quality rating based on quality column.THe purpose of categorizing them into bad,average and good wines is to give an idea about the wine whether it a bad,average or good wine by just looking at the graph rather than confusing a end user to interpret which wines are of good quality whether rating 5,6,7 is average or 3,4,5 rating values are bad(In some datasets it maybe the case where 1 is good while 10 is bad).The graphs adequately illustrate the factors that make good wines ‘good’ and bad wines ’bad.

Some of the struggles I have faced is mainly adjusting the chemical property names on the figure as initially variables names are covered up and it looked difficult for end user to interpret out of the plot.Next thing is choosing the appropriate graph for a given context and to group together different plot’s of chemical properties so that it makes easy for a end user to get a brief overview by just seeing a couple of plot’s instead of plotting graphs seperately based on chemical properties.

Some limitation in the dataset is due to more data is based on quality ratings 5 and 6.Less data is provided on bad(3,4) and good(7,8) quality rating wines. If the data set almost equal amount number of observations based on individual quality rating then we can be more certain regarding the correlation between chemical components and the wine quality.I would like to improve more on adding colors and using different styles in the plot to make my project look more presentable.Next choosing different population of wine tasters which would help further strengthen similarities in the data.
